elements.title: Self-Portrait with Cigarette
elements.contents: ... that the 1895 painting Self-Portrait with Cigarette (pictured) by Edvard Munch was met with criticism of his amorality and "degeneration"?

elements.title: Robert Bell
elements.contents: ... that in 1776 Robert Bell was commissioned by Thomas Paine to print Common Sense, considered the most inciteful work of the American Revolution?

elements.title: Raytheon 704
elements.contents: ... that the Raytheon 704, which cost more than $10,000 in 1970, was the first computer used for playing games by mail?

elements.title: Marie Surcouf
elements.contents: ... that Marie Surcouf was the president of Stella, a club for French women aeronauts?

elements.title: Engine No. 1
elements.contents: ... that investment fund Engine No. 1 waged a successful proxy battle against ExxonMobil despite owning only 0.02 percent of the oil company's shares?

elements.title: Hans Haselböck
elements.contents: ... that Hans Haselböck, later an international concert organist and professor at the Vienna Music Academy, began 65 years as organist at the Dominican Church, Vienna, on 4 November 1949?

elements.title: Reichsoberhandelsgericht
elements.contents: ... that for more than six decades no federal supreme court existed in the German territories until the Reichsoberhandelsgericht was formed in 1869?

elements.title: The Man Who Died Twice
elements.contents: ... that a reviewer said that Richard Osman's The Man Who Died Twice has "more holes than a dodgy knitting pattern" but he "enjoyed every minute"?
